<h4>Scrollable Collapse</h4>

<p>Tables may extend beyond the width of a screen, even once all whitespace is collapsed out. The <code>scrollable-collapse</code> class denotes that a table should not exceed 100% of its parent container, but if the data inside is wider than the parent container, then the user will be given the ability to scroll the table.</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">&lt;table class="table scrollable-collapse"&gt;
    &lt;td&gt;&lt;!-- Content wider than table container --&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;</pre>

<table class="table scrollable-collapse">
    <tr>
        <td class="primary" style="min-width:400px; width:400px;">Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Etiam pulvinar sem a sem venenatis aliquam.</td>
        <td class="secondary" style="min-width:400px; width:400px;">Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Etiam pulvinar sem a sem venenatis aliquam.</td>
        <td class="tertiary" style="min-width:400px; width:400px;">Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Etiam pulvinar sem a sem venenatis aliquam.</td>
        <td class="neutral" style="min-width:400px; width:400px;">Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Etiam pulvinar sem a sem venenatis aliquam.</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<p>This effect is achieved by applying a scrollable wrapper around the table. This occurs during the window load event; however, if the page is modified after load, newly added elements may be initialized such as:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">$('.table.scrollable-collapse').blocks().overflowScrollable('init');</pre>

<p>The Javascript initializer may alsobe bypassed by applying its wrapper directly, such as:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">&lt;div class="overflow-scroll"&gt;
    &lt;table class="table scrollable-collapse"&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;&lt;!-- Content wider than table container --&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
    &lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</pre>

<h4>Table Caption</h4>

<p>The <code>.table</code> element has built-in support for <code>caption</code>:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">&lt;table class="table"&gt;
    &lt;caption&gt;&lt;!-- Caption Text --&gt;&lt;/caption&gt;
    &lt;tr&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;&lt;!-- Col 1 --&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;&lt;!-- Col 2 --&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;&lt;!-- Col 3 --&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;</pre>
<table class="table bordered">
    <caption>Caption Text</caption>
    <tr>
        <td>Col 1</td>
        <td>Col 2</td>
        <td>Col 3</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<h5>Bottom Caption</h5>

<p>The <code>caption</code> element supports bottom positioning as <code>caption.bottom</code>:</p>

<pre class="prettyprint">&lt;table class="table"&gt;
    &lt;caption class="bottom"&gt;&lt;!-- Caption Text --&gt;&lt;/caption&gt;
    &lt;tr&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;&lt;!-- Col 1 --&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;&lt;!-- Col 2 --&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;&lt;!-- Col 3 --&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;</pre>
<table class="table bordered">
    <caption class="bottom">Caption Text</caption>
    <tr>
        <td>Col 1</td>
        <td>Col 2</td>
        <td>Col 3</td>
    </tr>
</table>

